Netflix Movies and TV Shows

Puja Handini

2024/06/30

Introduction

Photo by Thibault Panin on Unsplash

About this Dataset

Netflix is one of the most popular media and video streaming platforms. They have over 8000 movies or tv shows available on their platform, as of mid-2021, they have over 200M Subscribers globally. This tabular dataset consists of listings of all the movies and tv shows available on Netflix, along with details such as - cast, directors, ratings, release year, duration, etc.

Goals

The goal is to clean the data, do some EDA, make pretty graphs and charts, maybe finally will gain some insight about the data, including:

  1. Understanding what content is available in different countries
  2. Identifying similar content by matching text-based features
  3. Network analysis of Actors / Directors and find interesting insights
  4. Does Netflix has more focus on TV Shows than movies in recent years.
  5. Has Duration of movies over the years increased or decreased.
  6. Compare ratings of TV Shows and Movies and determine how they are rated.

From the summary above we discovered some columns are not formatted correctly. - type - country - date_added - release_year - rating - listed_in

netflix$type <- as.factor(netflix$type)
netflix$country <- as.factor(netflix$country)
netflix$date_added <- mdy(netflix$date_added)
netflix$release_year <- as.factor(netflix$release_year)
netflix$rating <- as.factor(netflix$rating)
netflix$listed_in <- as.factor(netflix$listed_in)

Explorations

Let us determine whether Netflix has been more focused on TV shows or movies.

type_counts <- table(netflix$type)

barplot(type_counts, 
        main = "Movies vs TV Shows", 
        xlab = "Type", 
        ylab = "Count", 
        col = "dark blue", 
        cex.main = 2, 
        cex.lab = 1.5, 
        border = NA, 
        axes = FALSE)

# Adding a box around the plot
box()

Netflix is more focus on Movies

We will then create visualizations for the top nations that Netflix targets with its movies and TV shows. First, we will create a new dataframe for just movies

# Load necessary library
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
# Assuming your data frame is named 'netflix_movies'
movies <- netflix %>%
  filter(type == "Movie") %>%
  filter(country != "") %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarize(number = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(number)) %>%
  slice(1:10)

# Display the movies data frame
head(movies)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   country        number
##   <fct>           <int>
## 1 United States    2058
## 2 India             893
## 3 United Kingdom    206
## 4 Canada            122
## 5 Spain              97
## 6 Egypt              92
# Create a bar plot
# Setting up the margins to accommodate large text
par(mar = c(12, 5, 5, 2)) # Adjust bottom margin to fit long country names

# Create the bar plot
barplot(
  height = movies$number,
  names.arg = movies$country,
  main = "Top Ten Countries - Movies",
  xlab = "",
  ylab = "Number of Movies",
  col = "dark blue",
  las = 2, # Rotate x-axis labels
  cex.names = 10, # Adjust size of x-axis labels
  cex.main = 10, # Adjust size of the title
  cex.lab = 10 # Adjust size of the axis labels
)

# Adding a box around the plot
box()
